<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mubarak Meets Kozyrev, Calls Ties `Excellent' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mubarak Meets Kozyrev, Calls Ties `Excellent' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0305174694 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1625 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0305174694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 3 May (MENA)--President Husni Mubarak 
received a message from Russian President Boris Yeltsin. 
  Following his audience with Mubarak today, Russian Foreign 
Minister Andrey Kozyrev also said that the message invites 
President Mubarak to visit Moscow soon. He added that he 
believes the visit will be made soon. 
  Kozyrev said that President Mubarak has a broad and unique 
view of the region and its problems. 
  He praised the excellent relations between Presidents 
Mubarak 
and Yeltsin and added that he congratulated President Mubarak on 
his birthday tomorrow, which coincides with a historic event, 
namely, the signing of the Palestinian-Israeli Agreement. He 
said Russia is looking forward to this day and this celebration, 
which will crown the strenuous efforts exerted to solve this 
difficult problem. 
  He went on to say that President Mubarak has declared 
Egypt's 
commitment to continue its peace process efforts. He added that 
Russia too is committed as a cosponsor of the Middle East peace 
efforts on the other tracks. 
  He stressed in this regard that Russia is committed to every 
track and that it maintains constant contact with Damascus. He 
said that Russia is trying to bring the Syrian and Israeli 
viewpoints closer and their outcome will appear later. 
  The Russian foreign minister stressed that his country 
supports the Palestinian issue politically and diplomatically. 
He noted that Palestinian president Yasir 'Arafat was in Moscow 
two weeks ago and held detailed talks with the Russian 
leadership. He said: We will help the Palestinians with some 
technical means to enable them to deal with whatever problems 
they might face in the stage after next, such as problems 
relating to borders. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

