<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Majali on Egyptian Ties, al-'Aqabah </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Majali on Egyptian Ties, al-'Aqabah </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0305163994 Amman Radio Jordan Network in Arabic 1500 GMT 3 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0305163994 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Radio Jordan Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Dr. 'Abd-al-Salam al-Majali met with 
Egyptian media representatives and delegates at the Prime 
Ministry today. These media men came to Jordan in order to 
report on the meetings of the Higher Jordanian-Egyptian 
Committee. During the meeting, the prime minister discussed 
bilateral relations and the regional situation. Here are more 
details: 
  Prime Minister Dr. 'Abd-al-Salam al-Majali welcomed the 
resumption of the meetings of the Higher Jordanian-Egyptian 
Committee. He said: We hope these meetings will be a 
foundation stone for reinstating work among the Arab states in 
the required way. He also pointed out the importance of 
coordination between the two fraternal countries, particularly 
in this phase. 
  The prime minister explained that the agenda of the meetings 
includes many issues and topics, led by consolidating political 
relations between the sisterly countries and discussing a number 
of economic issues, such as exports, protocols, dealing with 
trucks, transportation, the Arab bridge, and electric power 
connection. 
  Dr. al-Majali said that the Arab world is now passing 
through 
a crucial stage, that facts and events are accelerating rapidly, 
and that the Arab world is still unaware of the serious phase we 
are passing through because it is still dealing, to a limited 
degree, with the reasons for differences, but no genuine 
attempts have been made to remove these differences and deal 
with the new facts. 
  Al-Majali added that the real features of the new world 
order 
have not yet become clear, except for the fact that the United 
States is the country that is currently dominating this order. 
He noted that the character of the regional order that could 
prevail in our region has not yet become clear. The prime 
minister asserted that if the Arabs do not act before it is too 
late, do not reach understanding, and do not achieve accord, a 
regional order could be arranged and imposed on them. Such an 
order could affect the Arabs for a long period of time. 
  Al-Majali asserted that there is no room for spectators in 
such an order, and that we, the Arabs, should play an effective 
and influential role in this order. 
  The prime minister reviewed the siege imposed on the port of 
al-'Aqabah and the efforts that the Jordanian king and 
government have made to resolve this issue, as a result of which 
Jordan has sustained great financial losses that reflected 
negatively on the performance of the Jordanian economy. He said 
that since the meeting held between His Majesty King Husayn and 
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher in London last week 
no ship bound for al-'Aqabah has been intercepted. He added 
that the Jordanian proposal that the international company 
Lloyds supervise the dealings with cargo bound for the port of 
al-'Aqabah was approved. Al-Majali explained that some matters 
pertaining to this issue are still being studied. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

