<DOCNO> FBIS4-58443 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes086yy_94025" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-086 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Pre-Ceremony Events, Negotiations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Pre-Ceremony Events, Negotiations </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    `Insignificant' Points Left for Later </H4>

<F P=102> NC0405060794 Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network in 
Arabic 0400 GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0405060794 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Husni Mubarak has met for the second time 
with members of the Palestinian and Israeli delegations to 
continue his extensive consultations and discussions with them. 
The Palestinian side was lead by Yasir 'Arafat while the 
Israeli side was lead by Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin. 
  President Mubarak has been following up on the talks between 
the two sides, which lasted for approximately six hours, ending 
at 0130 this morning. President Mubarak met with the 
delegations immediately afterwards. 
  Dr. Nabil Sha'th, political adviser to Palestinian President 
Yasir 'Arafat, has stated that the Palestinian-Israeli agreement 
will be signed today, adding that everything has been resolved. 
Dr. Sha'th made these remarks following the Palestinian-Israeli 
talks that ended at 0205 this morning. 
  Regarding the differences that existed between the two 
sides, 
Sha'th said that solutions were found for all these points, with 
the support of President Husni Mubarak, Foreign Minister 'Amr 
Musa, and U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher. He added: 
Negotiations always involve give and take and we have reached 
an agreement that we are satisfied with. 
  Concluding his remarks, Sha'th said he was pleased with what 
has been achieved. He added that the beginning is always 
important because this is the first time in the history of the 
Palestinian people that they have had a chance to rule 
themselves by themselves on their own territory. He added: 
This is not all we want, it is just a start. 
  Foreign Minister Musa said following the Palestinian-Israeli 
talks that the agreement for the implementation of the 
Declaration of Principles will be signed at 1100 [0800 GMT] this 
morning. He added that all the outstanding issues had been 
settled and that the details will be made public today. He 
added: I will not announce anything on behalf of the 
Palestinians or the Israelis. Everything has been discussed in 
detail on the maps related to the agreement. 
  Asked if an agreement has been reached on the size of 
Jericho, Musa said that the area of Jericho has been increased 
by several kilometers, provided this is taken into consideration 
[as heard]. Regarding the guards at the crossing points, Musa 
said a certain agreement has been reached over this point. 
  Musa expressed his happiness at reaching an agreement, 
noting 
that some insignificant points have been left for a later stage. 
  Regarding the release of the Palestinian prisoners, Musa 
said 
this matter was discussed and many of them will be released. 
The foreign minister added that the question of territorial 
water was also discussed. 
  On U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher's role in the 
talks, Musa noted that Christopher played a very important role. 
Asked if President Mubarak played a role in persuading 'Arafat, 
Musa said: President Mubarak has persuaded all parties, not 
just 'Arafat, to be flexible. 
  Asked why President Mubarak spent so many hours in the 
negotiations for the first time, Musa said that it is natural 
for President Mubarak to be present throughout the duration of 
the talks, since Egypt is the country that has been devoting its 
efforts to solve the Palestinian issue for more than 40 years. 
He added that Egypt is also the host country for the signing 
ceremony of this historic agreement between the Palestinians and 
Israelis. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-58444 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes086yy_94026" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-086 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Pre-Ceremony Events, Negotiations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Pre-Ceremony Events, Negotiations </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Final Areas of Discord in Talks Detailed </H4>

<F P=102> TA0405051794 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 0405 GMT 4 May 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0405051794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Arye Gus and Shlomo Raz in Cairo -- live] </F>
  [Excerpts] [Gus] Prime Minister Rabin, 'Arafat, President 
Mubarak, Foreign Minister Musa, Secretary of State Christopher, 
and the heads of the delegations to the autonomy talks sat for 
eight hours last night until they settled all the disputed 
issues and announced that the agreement would be signed today at 
1100. 
  Last night's session was very contentious. It was fraught 
with mutual accusations about reneging on decisions and earlier 
positions, and with demands to reopen issues which had already 
been finalized. At times, the atmosphere was one of 
near-crisis. Occasionally, there were loud verbal exchanges, and 
U.S. Secretary of State Christopher had to intervene to calm 
'Arafat down. 
  At 0215 [2315 GMT], Nabil Sha'th and 'Amr Musa came out of 
the room to face the press, and Musa announced: There is an 
agreement. The sides held discussions and finalized all the 
details of the agreement. 
  Following are the outstanding issues the draft committees 
left to Rabin and 'Arafat to finalize: 
  Jericho's autonomous area: The area from which Israel will 
withdraw has been expanded to 62 km, far less than what the 
Palestinians demanded. However, the size and fate of this area 
may be brought up for further discussion at a later stage. In 
other words, this issue remains open. 
  Positioning a Palestinian policeman on the Allenby Bridge: 
Israel refused to accept this demand, and a policeman will not 
be positioned on the bridge. This issue may also be brought up 
for further discussion at a later stage. 
  Releasing prisoners: This was one of the toughest problems. 
Israel refused to release more than the 5,000 prisoners that had 
been agreed earlier. As may be recalled, the Palestinians had 
demanded the release of Hamas [Islamic Resistance Movement] and 
Islamic Jihad members who would in exchange undertake a 
commitment to stop engaging in terror and to support the 
Declaration of Principles. These terrorists will not be 
released at this point, but their case may be brought up for 
further discussion by the security liaison committee to be 
established at a later stage. 
  Territorial waters: The area to be given to the Palestinians 
has been expanded from 3 to 6 miles. They will also be given 
fishing rights in another 6 miles further out to sea. 
  Security activities: This is a very important issue which 
could cause problems and disputes in the future. The area of 
activity has been increased to 75 meters on each side of the 
east-west roads. In any event, the Palestinians will not have 
the right to detain or imprison Israelis, and they will have to 
summon a joint patrol. The Palestinian police force will not be 
allowed to detain uniformed Israeli security troops and 
vehicles. Israel will have the right and prerogative to any 
immediate reaction -- or engagement [last word in English], as 
this is defined in the agreement -- to any operation or incident 
which might endanger lives or property. However, the aim will be 
to end the incident and to defer its handling to the Palestinian 
police force as soon as possible. [passage omitted] 
  [Raz] Another decision made last night was to append several 
letters to the agreement. One letter deals with an issue which 
had been finalized, but the Israeli delegation nevertheless 
pressed to put it in writing: Yasir 'Arafat will not be able to 
enter the area bearing the title of president, but that of 
chairman of the PLO. 
  Another issue spelled out in a letter has to do with the 
talks about the early transfer of power in other areas of the 
West Bank other than Jericho, which will begin at once. This 
issue had been in dispute for many months and was raised in 
Washington more than once. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

