<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Turkey's Cetin Welcomes `Historic' Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Turkey's Cetin Welcomes `Historic' Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0405155194 Ankara ANATOLIA in Turkish 1505 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0405155194 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo (AA) -- Ali Simsek report -- Foreign Minister 
Hikmet Cetin has said that the Israeli-Palestinian agreement 
signed in Cairo, the capital of Egypt, today is important for 
the entire world. 
  Cetin, who is in Cairo to attend the signing ceremony of the 
agreement, assessing the agreement said that it will affect the 
region in many ways. 
  Stressing that the path taken has no return and that it will 
lead to peace and stability, Cetin said: This region which 
allocates all its resources to armament, clashes and war will 
now, to a great extent, allocate them to the development of the 
region and the peoples within the framework of cooperation. 
  Cetin noted that Turkey, which is a democratic and secular 
country in the region, can make significant contributions to the 
Middle East which is being restructured. 
  Pointing out that Turkey maintains good relations with all 
the regional countries, Cetin expressed satisfaction over the 
fact that the 45-year old war has ended in peace. He described 
this day as a `historic' one. 
  In an appeal to all the peoples of strife torn regions, 
Cetin 
said: No matter how much you fight, every war ends in peace. 
Let us secure peace before too much blood is spilled. 
  Pointing out that the agreement signed is just the 
beginning, 
Cetin concluded by saying that Syria, Jordan and Lebanon should 
join the peace process. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

