<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   PLO Cancels Contracts With Israeli Companies </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PLO Cancels Contracts With Israeli Companies </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0505092094 Tel Aviv DAVAR in Hebrew 5 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> TA0505092094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv DAVAR </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Mikhal Sela' and On Levi] </F>
  [Text] The PLO has ordered the cancellation of all 
contractual relationships between Civil Administration bodies in 
Gaza and Jericho and Israeli companies and public organizations. 
If this order is followed, the Palestinians in Gaza and Jericho 
might find themselves cut off from the supply of essential basic 
services, such as electricity, water, medication, gasoline, food 
products, and other essential consumption goods. 
  The Israeli delegation to the talks on civilian issues was 
notified of the move by Attorney Jamil al-Tarifi, head of the 
corresponding Palestinian delegation. DAVAR learned this from 
senior members of the Israeli delegation. The order came as an 
unpleasant surprise to the Israeli delegation and caused grave 
concern regarding the immediate future. The Civil 
Administration had asked to hand over the management of the 
affairs under its jurisdiction in an orderly manner that would 
include an overlap and transfer of the services it currently 
provides to the residents of Gaza and Jericho. 
  Furthermore, according to the agreements in principle, the 
Civil Administration system was supposed to be handed over to 
the Palestinians in its entirety and continue working in its 
present form. According to the Palestinian development plan, 
changes in this system were to be made gradually, based on 
available budgets. 
  The Israeli delegates proposed that the contracts be 
canceled 
in a few months, after the autonomy administration begins 
operating and is well established, but the Palestinians rejected 
the proposal. In view of this, all suppliers and companies with 
which the Civil Administration had contractual relations have 
been notified that their contracts will be terminated as of 17 
May. 
  The residents of the territories, who know that there are no 
other sources that can provide the services, were also surprised 
by the order. In discussions with them, it became apparent that 
Palestinians from outside the territories who are participating 
in the talks on civilian issues do not have the slightest idea 
about how life is run in the territories. For example, the 
Palestinians from outside the territories did not know that all 
electrical power in the territories comes from Israel. 
  The contracts in question provide the legal framework for 
the 
establishment of business ties between residents of the 
territories and Israeli suppliers, through the Civil 
Administration. The supply of power to Gaza, for example, is 
based on a contract between the Israel Electric Corporation and 
the municipalities and local councils in the Gaza Strip, 
according to which those bodies and not private persons are the 
"consumers" of the service. If these contracts are terminated 
before an alternative source of power is found, Gaza will be 
left without electricity. 
  It was learned yesterday that, after they realized that it 
might cause distress in the coming several weeks, members of the 
Palestinian delegation expressed regret over their decision to 
cancel the contracts. Nonetheless, the contracts were not 
renewed and no new ones have been signed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-58491 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes087yy_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-087 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Arab Countries, Israel Clash During Doha Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Arab Countries, Israel Clash During Doha Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0305171494 Paris AFP in English 1630 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0305171494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [by Taib Mahjoub] </F>
  [Text] Doha, 3 May (AFP)--Israeli and Arab negotiators 
clashed here Tuesday [3 May] on the first day of talks on Middle 
East disarmament aimed at halting the spiralling billion-dollar 
arms race in the region. 
  More than 40 states, including Israel and most Arab 
countries, were taking part in three days of multilateral 
discussions behind closed doors on a draft arms limitation deal 
for the region. 
  But trouble flared almost immediately as the Arab and 
Israeli 
delegations differed over how the talks should proceed, 
officials said. 
  A Western delegate said the head of the Israeli delegation, 
defence ministry director-general David Ivry, insisted "straight 
away that the session should adopt the draft, provoking Arab 
reticence." 
  An Arab delegate said: "Certain Arab participants, including 
Saudi Arabia, saw the proposed text as a political statement 
which has nothing to do with arms limitation." 
  The text specifies that arms limitation "must in no way come 
at the expense of one nation or provide advantages to another," 
and it must be approved "with the unanimous support of all 
parties concerned." 
  Under the terms of the 1991 Madrid peace conference which 
launched the disarmament talks, the draft declaration of 
principles on disarmament also includes a reference to "a 
reduction in the arsenals and personnel of the armed forces" in 
the region. 
  And it stresses that the Middle East should become an area 
where "weapons of mass destruction will be eliminated." 
  UN and EU envoys, as well as representatives of the United 
States and Russia, the co-sponsors of the Middle East peace 
process, were also attending the conference in the Qatari 
capital, held under tight security. 
  A Western delegate said: "The Arabs believe we must first 
agree on the elimination of weapons of mass destruction, while 
the Israelis insist the priority is to establish 
confidence-building measures in the region." 
  The Arab countries first want Israel to agree to practical 
measures on arms control, which should cover Israel's nuclear 
weapons capability. 
  Israel has vehemently denied that it possesses nuclear 
weapons, but Western experts have estimated it probably has up 
to 200 warheads. 
  "The fact that a state in the region possesses a nuclear 
strength perpetuates tension," said Qatari Foreign Minister 
Hamad Bin-Jasim Bin-Jabbur Al Thani. 
  He urged Israel to submit its nuclear potential to 
international supervision, and called on it to sign the Nuclear 
Non-Proliferation Treaty. 
  "Political stability in the region depends on an arms 
balance 
between Israel and the Arabs," Al Thani said. 
  A Western delegate said Israel "considers its technological 
superiority in defence matters is designed to ensure a balance 
in the region, as the Arabs have such great advantages in terms 
of population and territory." 
  In a bid to narrow Arab-Israeli differences, Western 
countries have proposed setting up collective structures 
including a crisis prevention centre to improve understanding 
and promote cooperation, a delegate said. 
  Russia has also suggested opening a regional military data 
bank "to exchange information on the state and position of 
forces and military manoeuvres in the region," another delegate 
said. 
  Ivry is heading a 21-strong team, the first to visit Qatar 
since the creation of Israel in 1948. 
  Informal talks between Arab countries and other participants 
are due to be held Wednesday on the sidelines of the main 
meeting. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-58492 </DOCNO>
