<H3> <TI>   Japan's Foreign Minister Kakizawa Arrives </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Japan's Foreign Minister Kakizawa Arrives </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0405141894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1406 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0405141894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Jerusalem, May 4 KYODO -- Japanese Foreign Minister 
Koji Kakizawa arrived in Tel Aviv on Wednesday [4 May] afternoon 
from Cairo as part of his Middle East trip, which will also take 
him to Jordan, Syria and the occupied territories. 
  In Cairo, he met with Egyptian President Husni Mubarak and 
PLO Leader Yasir 'Arafat and attended the signing ceremony of a 
historic agreement on limited Palestinian self-rule for Gaza and 
Jericho. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-58510 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes087_l_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-087 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  5 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pledges $200 Million to Autonomy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pledges $200 Million to Autonomy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0505110194 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in English 1000 GMT 5 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0505110194 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Japan has pledged $200 million to the Palestinian 
autonomy, which may be extended. This was announced this 
morning by Japan's Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa after meeting 
Palestinian leader Faysal al-Husayni in East Jerusalem. 
Earlier, he met with Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin in Tel Aviv. 
  [Begin recording] [Correspondent No'omi Segal] Japan has 
committed $200 million to the Palestinian autonomy, to be spread 
over the coming two years. Fifty million dollars have already 
been dispersed. The money was used to buy medical equipment for 
the Jericho hospital, to pay for the construction of Palestinian 
police facilities, and other development projects. The Japanese 
have also invited 70 Palestinians for training in the use of 
construction machinery. 
  Japanese Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa announced the aid 
package after meeting with Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin in Tel 
Aviv. He praised Rabin on the peace process, noting that he had 
been in Cairo for the signing ceremony. 
  Afterwards, Koji Kakizawa held talks in East Jerusalem with 
Palestinian leader Faysal al-Husayni. Emerging from the 
meeting, the Japanese foreign minister said he hoped the aid 
package would be extended and congratulated Israel and the PLO 
on signing the autonomy accord. 
  [Kakizawa] I am very pleased to be here at this historical 
moment. There are still critical issues on both sides -- on the 
Palestinian side and the Israeli side -- but we hope that your 
goodwill and your determination to get peace will solve many, 
many difficulties, and we hope that you will go forward for 
stability and peace in this region. 
  [Segal] Kakizawa continued on to Jericho, becoming the first 
foreign dignitary to visit since the signing. He will then 
cross into Jordan via the Allenby bridge and later visit Syria. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-58511 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes087_l_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-087 </AU>
Daily Report 
