<F P=100> LEBANON </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Awn Ready for `Direct Dialogue' With Syria </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    'Awn Ready for `Direct Dialogue' With Syria </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0405132294 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 1 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM0405132294 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "'Awn Expresses Willingness To Hold </F>
Direct Dialogue With Syria"] 
  [Text] Paris, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT -- Former Lebanese Prime 
Minister General Michel 'Awn yesterday expressed willingness to 
hold a direct dialogue with Syria with no Lebanese intermediary 
but on condition that "Damascus state its position clearly and 
in advance on a number of basic points which are not negotiable." 
  'Awn, who was talking to AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT from his 
residence 
in La Hutte Maison in the outskirts of Paris, said: "I hope 
that what I am saying will not be interpreted as appeasement." 
  'Awn added: "I do not agree to talk to the Lebanese regime. 
I prefer to talk to the party directly responsible on the 
ground. That party should, before the dialogue starts, make a 
number of commitments on two main issues, namely sovereignty and 
independence." 
  'Awn believes that "a practical demonstration of these two 
issues can be made by scheduling withdrawal of the Syrian Army 
from all Lebanese territory." 
  He described the claims made every now and then about 
attempts to open a dialogue with him as mere maneuvers. He 
added that "serious dialogue cannot be done through the press." 
'Awn asked: "What has become of the investigation into the 
crime of blowing up Sayyidat al-Najah church?" 
  He said that that case should be urgently dealt with because 
"it is a special case, independent of any other case." He said 
that "that incident was fabricated and opened the way to other 
crimes." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

