<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fatah Hawks Express Reservations on Peace Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fatah Hawks Express Reservations on Peace Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405143694 Paris France-2 Television Network in French 
1100 GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0405143694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-2 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] You can imagine that people in Israel followed 
this morning's events with a lot of attention, concern, and 
hope. The first Palestinian police officers have arrived in the 
occupied territories and in Gaza. As for our special 
correspondents, Isabelle Baechler and Patrick Voigt, they were 
in the company of Palestinians opposed to this autonomy treaty: 
  [Baechler] It is 1130 in a house in the Beach Camp district 
of the town of Gaza. Most of the men watching the historic 
moment of the signing in Cairo are on the list of terrorists who 
are most wanted by the Israeli Army. They are Fatah Hawks, the 
military branch of Yasir 'Arafat's organization. They are a bit 
sullen, despite the process of autonomy which is under way: 
  [Begin recording] [Unidentified Fatah Hawk, in Arabic, with 
superimposed French translation] We are happy. We have been 
waiting for this moment for a long time, but we fear that 
nothing may come of it. This is not the first time that 
agreements have been signed, but thus far we have not seen any 
change. 
  [Second unidentified Fatah Hawk in Arabic, with superimposed 
French translation] We are happy, but we are still wanted. 
Normal people are rejoicing, but we are still in hiding. 
  [Third unidentified Fatah Hawk in Arabic, with superimposed 
French translation] All right, they are signing today, but as 
recently as yesterday the Army erected roadblocks to capture us. 
[end recording] 
  [Baechler] The Fatah Hawks will not lay down their weapons 
until the new Palestinian authorities ask them to do so. What 
is different for them today is the fact that they feel closer to 
the new power. The entire population of Gaza is hoping. These 
800,000 Palestinians packed together on 375 square kilometers 
are waiting for signs of sovereignty from their future state. 
For the time being, nothing has changed. Israeli soldiers are 
still here, right in the center of Gaza. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

