<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Arafat Says Palestinians `Optimistic' About State </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    'Arafat Says Palestinians `Optimistic' About State </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0405182994 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 1710 GMT 4 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0405182994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with PLO Executive Committee Chairman Yasir </F>
'Arafat by Faridah al-Shubashi in Cairo on 4 May -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Al-Shubashi] Mr. President, on this day and after 
listening to your speech this morning, what do you have to say 
to your people in the occupied Palestinian territories, those 
who are optimistic or those who are pessimistic about the 
agreement? 
  ['Arafat] The first thing I would like to emphasize is that 
our people are optimistic, our people, the people who forge 
miracles, the people of martyrs, the people of sacrifices, the 
people against whom the conspiracy has been since the turn of 
the century until now [words indistinct] different opinions. 
However, I do not believe that there are pessimists among our 
people. This is the people [words indistinct] the Koran 
describes by saying: In this land are a people of exceeding 
strength [Koranic verse] 
  [Al-Shubashi] Mr. President, are you optimistic about the 
scope of the Palestinian state, God willing? 
  ['Arafat] [Words indistinct] the Palestinian people have 
actively contributed to building many of the Arab countries. 
They have contributed to Arab civilization and have largely 
contributed with their blood, spirit, ideas, muscles, 
experience, aspirations and [word indistinct] in all the Arab 
walks of life. I am confident [words indistinct] soon and very 
soon. Today, we laid the corner stone for the edifice of this 
Palestinian state. They see it as something far off, and we see 
it as something near [word indistinct]. 
  [Al-Shubashi] Mr. President, thank you. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-58590 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes087dd_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-087 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Husayni Sees Accord as 1st Step Toward Statehood </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Husayni Sees Accord as 1st Step Toward Statehood </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0405113894 Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT in Hebrew 4 May 94 p 7 </F>
<F P=103> TA0405113894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report on an interview with Faysal al-Husayni by Roni </F>
Shaqed in Jerusalem on 3 May] 
  [Text] "We are giving birth to a baby today, but it is 
weak. I love him because he is my child, but I am not pleased," 
Faysal al-Husayni, who laid the foundations for the peace accord 
yet was left behind in Jerusalem today, said. Like other 
Palestinian leaders in the territories, he will watch the 
signing ceremony on television. 
  "This is the first step toward a Palestinian state. I would 
have liked the first step to have been bigger, but it is a 
start," al-Husayni told YEDI'OT AHARONOT. "I thought we would 
be able to rule in Gaza and Jericho and tell the Israeli people: 
Yes, we can be free, build our country, and provide security 
for our people and yours. It now appears that we are not really 
being allowed to rule. Details introduced into the agreement 
take this opportunity away from the Palestinian people. If I 
must provide security, I require full control. 
  "The future of Jerusalem also troubles me. The closure harms 
religious life, and family ties are disrupted. We do not want a 
new agreement, but we are demanding a return to the previous 
situation in Jerusalem. I spoke with 'Arafat on the matter and 
asked him to raise the closure issue in his meeting with Rabin." 
  I asked him: We spoke in 1988, and you said that one day a 
Palestinian state would be set up. Did you think this would be 
the path taken? 
  "I thought that the process would take much longer. I spoke 
of 20 years; I thought demography would change the face of 
things." 
  How will we promote relations ties now? 
  "We have to change the Israeli mentality, and our side must 
see you differently as well. We have to believe in peace." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

