<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Update on Events 4, 5 May; Fighting Reported in Dhamar </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Update on Events 4, 5 May; Fighting Reported in Dhamar </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Salih, Djibouti Prime Minister Meet </H4>

<F P=102> JN0505092694 Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
1700 GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0505092694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brother Lieutenant General 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih, 
chairman of the Presidential Council, today received Djibouti 
Prime Minister Barkat Hamadou, who conveyed to him a letter from 
his brother Djibouti President Hassan Gouled. The letter dealt 
with bilateral relations, issues of interest to both fraternal 
countries, and developments in our country. 
  The letter stressed Djibouti's concern for stability in our 
country and its support of Yemen's unity and democratic policy 
as well as Djibouti's readiness to make any efforts or offer any 
good offices to help our country circumvent the challenges 
imposed by the crisis. The letter pointed out that Yemen's 
security and stability are of concern to Djibouti and other 
regional states, led by the Horn of Africa states. 
  The brother chairman of the Presidential Council voiced 
great 
appreciation for the genuine fraternal sentiments and the 
concern for supporting Yemeni unity, which is a pan-Arab gain 
for all sons of the Arab nation. He said our country cannot do 
without the efforts of any of its brethren, including those in 
Djibouti. The brother chairman pointed to the special 
Yemeni-Djibouti relations, which are close and historic ones. 
  The Yemeni News Agency, SABA', has learned that the brother 
chairman asked the Djibouti prime minister to convey a reply 
message to his brother President Hassan Gouled. He wished 
Yemeni-Djibouti relations further progress and prosperity. The 
meeting was attended by Deputy Prime Minister 'Abd-al-Wahhab 
al-Anisi, Foreign Minister Muhammad Salim Basindwah, and 
Djibouti Charge d'affires in Sanaa (Yusuf Omar Da'alah). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

