<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Update on Events 4, 5 May; Fighting Reported in Dhamar </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Update on Events 4, 5 May; Fighting Reported in Dhamar </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Representatives Comment on Events </H4>

<F P=102> JN0405134994 Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
1200 GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0405134994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The House of Representatives met this morning in a 
session chaired by Speaker Shaykh 'Abdallah Bin-Husayn al-Ahmar. 
The house reviewed and approved the minutes of the previous 
session. The people's representatives resumed their discussions 
of the contents of the report of the House of Representatives' 
committee in charge of investigating the incidents in the 'Imran 
region. 
  During the discussions, the representatives stressed that it 
is important for the House of Representatives to adopt a serious 
and responsible position on developments in the country. This 
is because the current situation requires the House to issue 
sound decisions that are free of leniency and placation. It was 
stressed that the Armed and Security Forces should stand 
alongside Constitutional legitimacy, seek to spare Yemeni blood, 
withdraw military forces and units stationed in what used to be 
called the border areas before unity between North and South 
Yemen was established, and transfer these units so they can 
undertake the duties of defending national sovereignty and 
protecting vital targets. 
  The people's representatives applauded the appeal issued by 
the chairmanship of the House of Representatives on 3 May to all 
personnel, noncommissioned officers, and officers of the Armed 
and Security Forces throughout all camps and positions in the 
Republic of Yemen. In the statement, the chairmanship noted the 
need to show wisdom and self-restraint and to reject any 
conspiracy calling for infighting. 
  The session lasted for four hours. The House of 
Representatives will resume its session tomorrow morning. 

</TEXT>

